description:
## Severity
Trivial
## Dimension
dry
## Location
src/coordinator/task_queue.rs:171-191 (add_dependency)
## Violation
```rust
if !self.tasks.iter().any(|t| t.id == from) {
    return Err(TaskQueueError::UnknownTask { missing: from });
}
if !self.tasks.iter().any(|t| t.id == to) {
    return Err(TaskQueueError::UnknownTask { missing: to });
}
// ...
if let Some(task) = self.tasks.iter_mut().find(|t| t.id == from) {
    task.depends_on.push(to);
}
```

Three full traversals of `self.tasks` per `add_dependency`. The `submit` path has the same shape (lines 150-159) doing the dep-exists check in a loop. With path_exists adding a depth-first walk, an `add_dependency` call on a 50-task queue can do hundreds of `iter().find()` traversals.

The trailing `if let Some(...) { ... }` is also a logic gap: the function returned Ok(()) without inserting the edge if the row vanished between the existence check and the mutation. That's unreachable today (single-threaded) but the silent no-success-no-error path is a footgun.

## Mandated refactor
Cache the row index once: `let from_idx = self.tasks.iter().position(|t| t.id == from).ok_or(...)?;` then use `self.tasks[from_idx].depends_on.push(to);`. Same pattern for `to`. Drop the `if let Some` and panic on the (now unreachable) lookup miss with `expect`, OR assert it via `unreachable!()`.
